    "summary": "api7.ai exposes 4 recorded developer surfaces—API7 Gateway Admin API, API7 Enterprise Developer Portal API, AISIX AI Gateway Proxy API, and AISIX AI Gateway Admin API—and all require auth via service-issued tokens/keys sent in headers (Dashboard token as `X-API-KEY` or Bearer for Gateway/ADC, Developer Portal Bearer token plus often `X-Portal-Developer-ID`, AISIX caller API key as Bearer or `x-api-key`, and AISIX admin key as Bearer or `x-api-key`).",
    "credentials": {
      "dashboard_token": {
        "type": "bearer",
        "label": "API7 Dashboard token",
        "generateUrl": "https://docs.api7.ai/api7-gateway/reference/obtain-dashboard-token",
        "setup": "Sign in to the API7 Enterprise Dashboard, then go to **Organization → Tokens** and click **Create Token**. API7 documents this token as usable for Admin API requests (`X-API-KEY`) and for ADC as `ADC_TOKEN`. Prefer a non-root user token with only the permissions you need. See [Obtain a Token from the Dashboard](https://docs.api7.ai/api7-gateway/reference/obtain-dashboard-token)."
      },
      "portal_token": {
        "type": "bearer",
        "label": "Developer Portal token",
        "generateUrl": "https://docs.api7.ai/api7-gateway/reference/developer-portal-api",
        "setup": "Use your API7 Developer Portal's authentication flow to obtain a Developer Portal token, then send it as `Authorization: Bearer <token>`. API7's Developer Portal API reference states every request must include a Developer Portal token; many operations also require `X-Portal-Developer-ID` with the active developer ID. See [Developer Portal API](https://docs.api7.ai/api7-gateway/reference/developer-portal-api)."
      },
      "aisix_admin_key": {
        "type": "bearer",
        "label": "AISIX admin key",
        "generateUrl": "https://docs.api7.ai/ai-gateway/reference/configuration-files.md",
        "setup": "Get the configured admin key from your self-hosted AISIX gateway `config.yaml`, as referenced by the docs. Use it for authenticated admin-listener routes as `Authorization: Bearer <admin-key>` or `x-api-key: <admin-key>`. See [Admin API Reference](https://docs.api7.ai/ai-gateway/reference/admin-api-reference.md) and [MCP Gateway](https://docs.api7.ai/ai-gateway/advanced-proxy-capabilities/mcp-gateway.md)."
      },
      "aisix_caller_api_key": {
        "type": "api_key",
        "label": "AISIX caller API key",
        "generateUrl": "https://docs.api7.ai/ai-gateway/advanced-proxy-capabilities/mcp-gateway.md",
        "setup": "Create a caller-facing API key through the AISIX Admin API or AISIX Cloud. The proxy docs say proxy requests use caller-facing API keys created through the Admin API or AISIX Cloud; for self-hosted setup, the MCP Gateway guide shows creating an `apikeys` Admin API resource after hashing the plaintext key. Clients then send the plaintext key as `Authorization: Bearer <caller-key>` or `x-api-key: <caller-key>`. See [Proxy API Reference](https://docs.api7.ai/ai-gateway/reference/proxy-api-reference.md) and [MCP Gateway](https://docs.api7.ai/ai-gateway/advanced-proxy-capabilities/mcp-gateway.md)."
      }
    },
